<subSubSection id="C3346555CD03FFE4FF204CEDB3B5FDDC" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B9136DECD03FFE4FF204CEDB3B5FDDC" blockId="10.[151,1436,319,668]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis id="B95AEACCCD03FFE4FF204CEDB222FE70" bold="true" box="[199,352,391,416]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Distribution.</emphasis>
The species was originally known only from the 
<typeStatus id="5495887CCD03FFE4FC7A4CE2B08FFE70" box="[925,973,392,416]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">type</typeStatus>
locality in 
<collectingCountry id="F339764ECD03FFE4FBB64CE2B7EFFE4F" box="[1105,1197,392,415]" name="Vanuatu" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Vanuatu</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFBF4B2FCD03FFE4FB5A4CEDB619FE4F" author="Sirenko" box="[1213,1371,391,415]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Sirenko, B. I. (2001) Deep-sea chitons (Mollusca, Polyplacophora) from sunken wood off New Caledonia and Vanuatu. Memoires du Museum national d'Histoire Naturelle, 185, 39 - 71." type="journal article" year="2001">
Sirenko 
<number id="3DE624F9CD03FFE4FAF84CEDB619FE4F" box="[1311,1371,391,415]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The present, equivocally identified material extends the range, with the majority of specimens known from the 
<collectingCountry id="F339764ECD03FFE4FAB84CC6B264FE37" name="Solomon Islands" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Solomon Islands</collectingCountry>
. The species is now known from 
<quantity id="4CD69B3BCD03FFE4FD574CA5B077FE37" box="[688,821,463,487]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.79" metricValueMax="8.36" metricValueMin="5.22" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="m" value="679.0" valueMax="836.0" valueMin="522.0">
522– 
<specimenCount id="9D28FD57CD03FFE4FD0E4CA5B077FE37" box="[745,821,463,487]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="generic">836 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
. Found living and feeding on sunken terrestrial plant remains.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3346555CD03FFE4FF204F72B7C0FD4C" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B9136DECD03FFE4FF204F72B7C0FD4C" blockId="10.[151,1436,319,668]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis id="B95AEACCCD03FFE4FF204F72B279FDE0" bold="true" box="[199,315,536,560]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is rare. it is distinctive for its small size (around 
<quantity id="4CD69B3BCD03FFE4FC004F7DB76AFDFF" box="[999,1064,535,559]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
in length); it is superficially very similar to a miniature version of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2E4D5DCD03FFE4FDF54F57B1DBFD84" box="[530,665,572,596]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Leptochiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="vanbellei">
<emphasis id="B95AEACCCD03FFE4FDF54F57B1DBFD84" box="[530,665,572,596]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">L. vanbellei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In 
<taxonomicName id="4C2E4D5DCD03FFE4FD2E4F57B012FD84" box="[713,848,572,596]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Leptochiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="deforgesi">
<emphasis id="B95AEACCCD03FFE4FD2E4F57B012FD84" box="[713,848,572,596]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">L. deforgesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, aesthetes are arranged in bundles of four micraesthetes around each megalaesthete; in 
<taxonomicName id="4C2E4D5DCD03FFE4FDD14F0BB1F9FDA8" box="[566,699,608,632]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Leptochiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="vanbellei">
<emphasis id="B95AEACCCD03FFE4FDD14F0BB1F9FDA8" box="[566,699,608,632]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">L. vanbellei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
each granule has only two micraesthetes per megalaesthete. Also, the girdle scales of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2E4D5DCD03FFE4FE974FEFB2B7FD4C" box="[368,501,644,668]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Leptochiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="deforgesi">
<emphasis id="B95AEACCCD03FFE4FE974FEFB2B7FD4C" box="[368,501,644,668]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">L. deforgesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have distinct ribs, where those in 
<taxonomicName id="4C2E4D5DCD03FFE4FC934FEFB0BAFD4C" box="[884,1016,644,668]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Leptochiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="vanbellei">
<emphasis id="B95AEACCCD03FFE4FC934FEFB0BAFD4C" box="[884,1016,644,668]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">L. vanbellei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are smooth.
</paragraph>
